	  	<h1 id="schemes" style="color: #5168A7;">Scheme Theory<br></h1> <br>
		<h3> List of exercises</h3> 
        We collect here a (incomplete) list of useful exercises. Since the Theory of Schemes can, at a first glance, be a bit abstract, we encourage the students to go trought many exercises to test their understanding of the various topics and notions introduced in class. The list indicates exercise from various sources indicated by an abbreviation, e.g. [H] Hartshorne's Algebraic Geometry, see the list Abbreviations. Some of the exercises are quite challenging and some of them will seem to be more easy: we hope that they will also serve as a starting point of interesting discussion among the students and with the lecturers.<br><br>
         <ol>
             <li><em>Sheaves</em>: [H] ch2 - 1.8, 1.9, 1.14, 1.15, 1.16, 1.21; [GW] 2.16; [EH] I-1, I-3.</li>
             <li><em>Affine Schemes</em>: [H] ch2 - 2.3, 2.5, 2.8, 2.10, 2.11; [GW] 2.7, 2.8, 2.19, 3.6, 3.7; [EH] I-20, I-22, I-25.</li>
             <li><em>Fiber Products</em>: [H] ch2 - 3.9, 3.10, 3.15; [GW] 4.6, 4.7, 4.8; [EH] I-46, I-47.</li>
             <li><em>...</em></li>
         </ol>
         <br>
         Abbreviations:
         <ul>
             <li> [H] = Hartshorne, Robin: <em>Algebraic geometry</em>, Graduate Texts in Mathematics, No. 52, Springer-Verlag (1977).</li>
             <li> [GW] = GÃ¶rtz, Ulrich and Wedhorn, Torsten: <em>Algebraic geometry I</em>, Advanced Lectures in Mathematics, Vieweg + Teubner, Wiesbaden (2010);</li>
             <li> [EH] = Eisenbud, David and Harris, Joe: <em>The geometry of schemes</em>, Graduate Texts in Mathematics, No. 197, Springer-Verlag (2000);</li>
         </ul>

	
    
